.TH XCOMM 1 "2026-05-15" "User Commands" "CLI-Improved Manual"
.SH NAME
xcomm \- compare two sorted files line-by-line (fail-safe version)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B xcomm
.I <file1>
.I <file2>
.SH DESCRIPTION
A robust, protective wrapper for the standard \fBcomm\fR utility.
.PP
The native system \fBcomm\fR requires both input files to be lexically sorted 
prior to execution. If unsorted inputs are provided, the system binary fails 
silently, emitting incomplete or corrupted matching data without warning. 
.PP
This refined version runs defensive checks on the inputs using \fBsort \-C\fR. 
If either file is found to be unsorted, it leverages shell process substitution 
to sort the streams dynamically on the fly, guaranteeing accurate comparison 
results while leaving the original files on the disk untouched.
.SH TECHNICAL NOTES
.TP
\fBDefensive Checking:\fR
The script uses \fBsort \-C\fR to audit the files. This check is fast and 
computationally inexpensive, ensuring that already-sorted files suffer zero 
performance penalty.
.TP
\fBMemory Efficiency:\fR
By using bash process substitution \fB<()\fR, sorted data streams are piped 
directly into the \fBcomm\fR execution block via anonymous named pipes. This 
avoids the frcition of creating, tracking, and clearing out temporary files on the disk.
.SH INSTALLATION
Copy the script from the GitHub repository to your $PATH, typically /usr/local/bin.
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
Returns the exit status of the underlying \fBcomm\fR command, or 1 if the incorrect 
number of file arguments is passed.
